oks\n| Episode: \"[[List of Lie to Me episodes#Season 2: 2009-2010|Bullet Bump]]\"\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Psych]]''\n| Dr. Donna Gooden\n| Episode: \"[[Dual Spires]]\"\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Perception (2012 TV series)|Perception]]''\n| Lacey Pinderhall\n| Episode: \"[[List of Perception episodes#Season 1 (2012)|86'd]]\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Rosewood (TV series)|Rosewood]]''\n| Brenda Downs\n| Episode: \"Keratin & Kissyface\" \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Twin Peaks (season 3)|Twin Peaks]]''\n| Laura Palmer / Carrie Page\n| 3 episodes \n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Correspondence''\n| Mona (Voice)\n| Web series short, 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Limetown (TV series)|Limetown]]''\n| Alison Haddock \n| Web series, 2 episodes\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Voice role\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''Murder Mystery 3: Who Killed Brett Penance?''\n| Lucie Fairwell\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''Murder Mystery 4: Who Killed Taylor French?''\n| Lucie Fairwell\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[BioShock 2]]''\n| Gossiping Baby Jane Splicer\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Performer\n! Music video\n! Role\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[The Backbeat Band]]''\n| ''[[Money (That's What I Want)]]'' \n| [[Astrid Kirchherr]]\n|}\n\n==Stage credits==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Theatre\n! Notes\n|-\n| n/a\n| ''The Bad Seed''<ref name=\"25yearslatersite.com\">https://25yearslatersite.com/2019/09/13/sheryl-lee-discusses-her-acting-workshops-connecting-with-fans-and-more/</ref>\n| Mom\n|\n|\n|-\n| n/a\n| ''The Haunting of Hill House''<ref name=\"25yearslatersite.com\"/>\n| \n|\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''Crimes of the Heart''\n|\n| [[National Theatre Conservatory]]\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''Electric River''\n|\n| Pioneer Square Theater\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Emerald City''\n|\n| Empty Space Theatre\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Love Letters (play)|Love Letters]]''\n| Melissa Gardner\n| Canon Theater\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Salome (play)|Salome]]''\n| Salome\n| [[Circle in the Square Theatre]]\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| '' Love Letters''\n| Melissa Gardner\n| Kenan Auditorium\n|\n|}\n\n==Audiobook==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Secret Diary of Laura Palmer]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/2/15/14622944/twin-peaks-audiobook-secret-life-of-laura-palmer-sheryl-lee|work=The Verge|title=Audible is releasing an audiobook version of a Twin Peaks spinoff novel|date=February 15, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2017|author=Plaugic, Lizzie}}</ref>\n|Nominated\u2014[[Audie Award]] for Best Female Narrator\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* \"''Woman of the Year: Laura Palmer''\".  ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''.  Volume 114.  Issue 2.  August 1990.  p.&nbsp;118\u2013119.\n* \"Twin Peaks' ''Sheryl Lee Goes from Dead Role to Dead Ringer''\", by Laurie Grassi.  ''[[TV Guide]]'' (Canada).  Volume 14: Issue 45.  November 10, 1990.\n* \"''Sheryl's Peril''\", by James Wolcott.  ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.  February 1992.  p.&nbsp;106\u2013107.\n* \"''Sur la Croisette: Arr\u00eats sur Images sur Quarante-Cinq Acteurs''\",  by Michel Rebichon.  ''[[Studio Magazine|Studio]]'' (France).  Issue 62: Sp\u00e9cial Cannes 1992.  May 1992.  p.&nbsp;138.\n* \"''5 July 1992 Sheryl Lee Interview''\", by Robert Getz.  ''[[Wrapped In Plastic]]''.  Issue 16.  April 1995.\n* \"''Sheryl Lee''\",  by Silvia Bizio.  ''[[MAX Magazine|Max]]'' (Italy).  September 1992.  p.&nbsp;128\u2013133.\n* \"''Laura Palmer Lives!''\", by Jeff Dawson.  ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]''.  December 1992.  p.&nbsp;54\u201355.\n* [http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1285/is_n3_v24/ai_15409055 \"''A New Peak for Sheryl Lee''\"], by Graham Fuller.  ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]''.  March 1994.\n* \"''Sheryl Lee Interview''\", by Craig Miller & John Thorne.  ''[[Wrapped In Plastic]]''.  Issue 16.  April 1995.  p.&nbsp;5\u201310.\n* [http://www.twin-peaks.fr/articles/interview/sheryllee.html \"''The Bliss of Being Sheryl Lee''\"], by Edward Guthman.  ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''.  June 8, 1997.\n* [http://www.ew.com/ew/report/0,6115,281957_2_0_,00.html \"''There's No Killing Laura Palmer: The Unstoppable'' Twin Peaks ''Ingenues''\"], by Troy Patterson.  ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''.  February 13, 1998.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928161925/http://www.tszuj-it.com/articles/ted/esquire18.html \"''Three Women, One Peek: Sheryl Lee, Sherilyn Fenn and Lara Flynn Boyle Finally Leave David Lynch's World. Almost''\"],  by Ted Allen.  ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''.  October 1998.\n* \"''Sheryl Lee on'' Vampires\", by John Thonen.  ''[[Femme Fatales (magazine)|Femme Fatales]]''.  Volume 7: Issue 6.  November 1998.  p.&nbsp;16\u201317.\n* [http://www.peta.org/features/sheryl-lee.aspx \"''Sheryl Lee Takes a Swipe at Animal Acts''\"].  ''[[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA's Animal Times]]''. Summer 1999.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070625235004/http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/people/341982,CNT-News-cover_15.article \"''Welcome to the'' TP ''Time Warp. Where Are They Now? Fire Walk with the Cast of'' Twin Peaks\"],  by Paige Wiser.  ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''.  April 15, 2007.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q233593|b=no|wikt=no|s=no|v=no|voy=no|q=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|n=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|0498247}}\n* {{Amg name|41511}}\n* [http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/SearchResult.aspx?s=&retailCheck=&Type=PN&CatID=DATABIN_CAST&ID=261367&AN_ID=&searchedFor=Sheryl_Lee_ Sheryl Lee] at the [[American Film Institute]] catalog\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Sheryl}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Boulder, Colorado]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Expatriate actresses in Germany]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Sheryl Lee 01 (14948055197).jpg\n| caption = Lee at the [[Fan Expo Canada]] 2014\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|4|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Augsburg]], [[Bavaria]], [[Germany|West Germany]]\n| death_date = \n| birth_name = Sheryl Lynn Lee\n| othername = \n| awards = '''[[Sundance Film Festival|Spirit of Sundance Award]]'''<br>1995 ''for her body of work''\n| spouse = Jesse Diamond<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 2000; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 200?)\n| children = 1\n| alma_mater= [[University of Colorado Boulder]]\n| website = {{url|http://www.belovednature.com/}}<br>{{url|http://www.theactorsdirectorworkshop.com/}}\n| years_active = 1986\u2013present\n| occupation = [[Actor|Actress]]\n}}\n'''Sheryl Lynn Lee''' (born April 22, 1967) is an [[Americans|American]] film, stage, and television actress. After studying acting in college, Lee relocated to [[Seattle, Washington]] to work in theater, where she was cast by [[David Lynch]] as [[Laura Palmer]] and [[Maddy Ferguson]] on the 1990 [[cult television|cult]] [[TV series]] ''[[Twin Peaks]]'' and in the 1992 film ''[[Twin Peaks: Fire Walk with Me]]''. After completing ''[[Twin Peaks]]'', she returned to theater, appearing in the title role of ''[[Salome (play)|Salome]]'' on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] opposite [[Al Pacino]].\n\nHer film roles include as [[Astrid Kirchherr]] in ''[[Backbeat (movie)|Backbeat]]'' (1994), as well as a lead role in the drama ''[[Mother Night (film)|Mother Night]]'' (1996), the role of Katrina in [[John Carpenter]]'s ''[[Vampires (1998 film)|Vampires]]'' (1998) and the part of April in ''[[Winter's Bone]]'' (2010). She has had recurring roles on such television series as ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]'' (2005\u20132006) and ''[[Dirty Sexy Money]]'' (2007\u20132009). She reprised her role of Laura Palmer in the [[Showtime (network)|Showtime]] revival of ''[[Twin Peaks (season 3)|Twin Peaks]]'' (2017).\n\n==Early life==\nLee was born in [[Augsburg]], [[Bavaria]], [[West Germany]] to an artist mother and architect father;<ref name=FR>{{cite web|work=Filmreference.com|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/30/Sheryl-Lee.html|title=Sheryl Lee}}</ref> the first of three children. She grew up in [[Boulder, Colorado]], United States, where she was a graduate of [[Fairview High School (Boulder, Colorado)|Fairview High School]] (class of 1985). After graduating, Lee moved to [[Pasadena, California]] where she studied at the [[American Academy of Dramatic Arts]], and later attended the [[North Carolina School of the Arts]], the [[National Theatre Conservatory]] in Denver, and the [[University of Colorado]].\n\nAfter several years of studying, Lee moved to [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] where she acted in several stage plays<ref>{{cite web|url=http://twinpeaksarchive.blogspot.com/2013/05/exclusive-sheryl-lee-interview-part-one.html|title=Exclusive Sheryl Lee Interview |work= Twin Peaks on Showtime |accessdate= 28 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/nerd/2014/04/11/sheryl-lee-laura-palmer-twin-peaks-colorado-boulder/1856/2/|work=Denver Post|title=Sheryl Lee on the \"Twin Peaks\" anniversary, her Colorado roots and why she\u2019s coming back this summer|author=Wenzel, Jon|date=11 April 2014|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref> and appeared in several commercials.<ref name=burns>{{cite web|url=https://wrappedinplastictwinpeaks.com/2015/02/24/shes-filled-with-secrets-the-sheryl-lee-interview-complete-and-unedited/|work=Wrapped In Plastic|title=She's Filled With Secrets: The Sheryl Lee Interview|date=February 24, 2015|author=Burns, Andy|accessdate=December 28, 2016}}</ref> She studied with theater director Mark Jenkins at the now-defunct Empty Space Theater in Seattle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/archives/twin-peeks-sheryl-lee-is-accused-of-murder-this-time/article_e64bfe26-843a-5dbb-bd56-98c09cdc3d87.html|work=Tulsa World|title=`Twin Peeks' Sheryl Lee Is Accused of Murder This Time Around on NBC|last=Buck|first=Jerry|date=February 17, 1991|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1986\u20141993: Career beginnings and ''Twin Peaks''===\n[[File:Sheryl Lee (2081514525).jpg|thumbnail|right|Lee arriving at the 1990 [[Emmy Award]]s]] \nLee's first television role was as the dead [[Laura Palmer]] in the [[television]] [[television program|series]] ''[[Twin Peaks]]''. To save on money, creator David Lynch intended to cast a local girl from [[Seattle]] \"just to play a dead girl\".<ref name=\"rodley\">{{cite book |title=[[Lynch on Lynch]] |first=Chris |last=Rodley |publisher=[[Faber & Faber Limited]]|location=[[London]]|date=1997|isbn=0-571-19548-2}}</ref> The local girl ended up being Sheryl Lee. \nLynch asked Lee to audition for him after seeing a publicity photo of her in Seattle from one of the plays she was starring in at the time.<ref>{{cite journal|work=Details|year=1991|title=With Laura Palmer Wrapped, Sheryl Lee Plays A Role Based on a Nightmare Darker Than Twin Peaks Could Ever Be|author=Gliatto, Tom}} {{cite web |url=http://www.davidlynch.de/withlaurapalmer.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121151120/http://davidlynch.de/withlaurapalmer.html |archivedate=2010-11-21 }}</ref> \"But no one &mdash; not Mark, me, anyone &mdash; had any idea that she could act, or that she was going to be so powerful just being dead.\"<ref name=\"rodley\"/> Indeed, the image of Lee wrapped in plastic as well as her [[Homecoming Queen]]-Photo became one of the show's most enduring and memorable images. When Lynch shot the home movie that [[James Hurley (Twin Peaks)|James Hurley]] takes of [[Donna Hayward]] and Laura, he realized that Lee had something special. \"She did do another scene &mdash; the video with Donna on the picnic &mdash; and it was that scene that did it.\"<ref name=\"rodley\"/> As a result, Sheryl Lee became a semi-regular addition to the cast, appearing in flashbacks as Laura, and becoming a recurring character, Laura's cousin [[Maddy Ferguson]] later in the series (a role which was reportedly written because Lynch, impressed with her abilities, wanted to give her a fuller role on the show). She worked again with Lynch when she appeared as [[Glinda the Good Witch]] in ''[[Wild at Heart (film)|Wild at Heart]]'' (1990).\n\nShe also starred in the [[sequel#Prequels and interquels|prequel]] ''[[Twin Peaks: Fire Walk with Me]]'', which elaborated on events leading up to Laura Palmer's death. While the film itself was a critical and financial [[failure]] at the time of its release, Lee was praised by the critics for her performance, which earned her nominations at the [[Independent Spirit Awards]] and the [[Saturn Awards]] for Best Actress.\n\nIn 1992 Lee starred as Salome alongside [[Al Pacino]] in the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of [[Oscar Wilde]]'s ''[[Salome (play)|Salome]]'' in the Circle in the Square Theatre under the direction of Robert Allan Ackerman. The play co-starred [[Suzanne Bertish]], [[Esai Morales]] and [[Arnold Vosloo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/26/theater/review-theater-al-pacino-s-very-personal-vision-makes-a-splash.html|work=New York Times|title=Review/Theater; Al Pacino's Very Personal Vision Makes a Splash|author=Gussow, Mel|date=June 26, 1992|accessdate=April 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===1994\u20142004: ''Backbeat'' and Post-''Peaks'' career===\nIn 1994 she was cast as [[Astrid Kirchherr]] in the film ''[[Backbeat (movie)|Backbeat]]'', a [[bio-pic]] of the early career of [[The Beatles]] opposite [[Stephen Dorff]]. The following years, Lee played the part of Liza in [[Gary Walkow]]'s 1995 adaptation of [[Fyodor Dostoyevsky]]'s novella ''[[Notes from Underground]]'' opposite [[Henry Czerny]], the role of Helga and Resi Noth in the 1996 romantic war film ''[[Mother Night (film)|Mother Night]]'', based on [[Kurt Vonnegut]]'s 1961 [[Mother Night|novel of the same name]], starred alongside [[Craig Sheffer]] in ''[[Bliss (1997 film)|Bliss]]'' (1997) and played the role of Katrina in [[John Carpenter]]'s 1998 film ''[[Vampires (1998 film)|Vampires]]'' opposite [[James Woods]] and [[Daniel Baldwin]]. She played also a leading role in the 1999 [[crime drama film]] ''[[Angel's Dance]]'' with [[Kyle Chandler]] and [[Jim Belushi]] and starred as Dr. Sarah Church in the short lived series ''[[L.A. Doctors]]'' (1998\u20141999) which ran for a single season.\n\nLee starred opposite [[Anthony Michael Hall]] as the sweet but vengeful housewife Eve Robbins in the 2001 USA Cable movie ''Hitched''. In 2001 she presented the ''I Love 1990'' segment of the BBC's popular ''[[I Love the '90s (UK TV series)|I Love 1990s]]'' series. She played the leading role of Elinore Murphy in ''[[Children on Their Birthdays]]'' (2002), based on [[Children on Their Birthdays|the short story of the same title]] by [[Truman Capote]]. In the 2003 television series ''[[Kingpin (TV series)|Kingpin]]'', she played the role of Marlene Cadena opposite [[Yancey Arias]] and [[Bobby Cannavale]].\n\nIn 2004 Lee was the original choice for the role of Mary-Alice Young on ''[[Desperate Housewives]]''. It would have been the second time she would have played a dead character on a series; however, the producers ultimately chose to replace her with [[Brenda Strong]], as producers thought that Lee was not right for the part.<ref name=\"hit\">[[Charles McDougall|McDougall, Charles]] (January 5, 2005). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/3634415/Desperately-seeking-a-ratings-hit.html \"Desperately seeking a ratings hit\"]. ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. Retrieved August 15, 2010.</ref> Strong commented on the casting change for her character, explaining, \"I think it was a conceptual shift&nbsp;... There certainly wasn't something wrong with what [Lee] did. It was just that instead of vanilla they wanted chocolate, and I happened to be chocolate.\"\n\n===2005\u2014present: Return to television and Independent films===\n[[File:WW Chicago 2012 - Sheryl Lee 1 (7785836238).jpg|left|thumbnail|Sheryl attending the Wizard World Chicago in 2012]]\nIn 2005-06, she played the recurring role of [[Ellie Harp]], the biological mother of [[Peyton Sawyer]] (played by [[Hilarie Burton]]), who battles breast cancer, on the third season of the [[WB Network]] series ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]''.\nIn 2007 and 2008 Lee appeared on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] [[dramedy]] ''[[Dirty Sexy Money]]'' as Andrea Smithson, the mother of Brian Darling's ([[Glenn Fitzgerald]]) illegitimate child. Lee, along with several other ''Twin Peaks'' cast members, guest starred in a special ''Twin Peaks''-themed episode of ''[[Psych]]'' titled \"[[Dual Spires]].\" Other cast members reunited with Lee included [[Sherilyn Fenn]] (Audrey Horne), [[Dana Ashbrook]] (Bobby Briggs), [[Ray Wise]] (Leland Palmer), [[Lenny Von Dohlen]] (Harold Smith), [[Robyn Lively]] (Lana Budding Milford), and [[Catherine E. Coulson]] (The Log Lady). This episode marked the first time several ''Twin Peaks'' cast members had been reunited on television in almost two decades.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}\n\nIn 2010 she appeared in a supporting role as April in [[Debra Granik]]'s ''[[Winter's Bone]]'' (which won best picture at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] in 2010). The film is about a seventeen-year-old girl ([[Jennifer Lawrence]]) in the rural Ozarks, caring for her mentally-ill mother and her younger brother and sister, when she discovers that her father put their house and land up as a bond for a court appearance, at which he failed to appear. Lee won two Awards for ''Best Ensemble'' at [[Detroit Film Critics Society]] and [[Gotham Awards]], shared with the cast. Lee played Lucie Sliger in the 2011 crime thriller ''[[Texas Killing Fields]]'' alongside [[Jessica Chastain]], [[Sam Worthington]] and [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]].\n\nIn the art drama thriller ''[[White Bird in a Blizzard]]'' (2014), written and directed by [[Gregg Araki]], she played May opposite [[Shailene Woodley]] and [[Eva Green]]. In 2015, at the Twin Peaks UK Festival, Lee confirmed that she would be returning to ''Twin Peaks'' for the 2017 limited Showtime run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2015/01/laura-palmer-twin-peaks|title=Laura Palmer is Returning to Twin Peaks|work=Vanity Fair|author=Locker, Melissa|date=January 17, 2015|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 she appeared in a supporting role as Air in the [[Netflix]] production ''[[Rebirth (2016 film)|Rebirth]]'', which premiered at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]], and had a small part as Karen in ''[[Caf\u00e9 Society (2016 film)|Caf\u00e9 Society]]'', written and directed by [[Woody Allen]]. The film had its premiere at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]]. In 2017 she reprised her role as [[Laura Palmer]] in ''[[Twin Peaks (season 3)|Twin Peaks]]'' and also playing the part of Carrie Page, making it her third character in the series. Although she was credited in every one of the 18 episodes, most of her appearance was in [[archive footage]]. New material of her was seen in the episodes [[Part 2 (Twin Peaks)|Part 2]], [[Part 17 (Twin Peaks)|Part 17]] and [[Part 18 (Twin Peaks)|Part 18]]. The same year, she starred as Alley in the short film ''Dead Ink Archive'' by David Schendel, making it their second collaboration after the 1994 film ''The Can'' (which was filmed in the late 1980s). In 2018 Lee played one of the leads in the Teen-Thriller ''#SquadGoals'' as Emily Hodges.\n\nIn 2019, Lee returned to Theater, playing alongside [[Judd Nelson]] in ''[[Love Letters (play)|Love Letters]]''. She performed the play before in 1991 with [[Luke Perry]] and [[Tim Daly]] as co-stars.<ref>http://www.encorepub.com/love-letters-uncw/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Sheryl Lee.jpg|thumb|upright|Sheryl Lee at 42nd Emmy Awards (1990)]]\nLee dated [[David Duchovny]], who was one of her ''Twin Peaks'' cast-mates. She was at one time married to Jesse Diamond, a photographer and son of singer and songwriter [[Neil Diamond]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wonderwall.com/entertainment/tv/twin-peaks-cast-where-are-they-now-34553.gallery?photoId=185033 |work=Wonderwall |title=Sheryl Lee now - Twin Peaks cast |access-date=April 21, 2017 |author=Wedemeyer, Jessica|date=June 6, 2016}}</ref> They have a son, Elijah, born in 2000.<ref name=\"co\"/>\n\nIn 2014, she revealed that she had been diagnosed with a rare blood disorder called [[neutropenia]].<ref name=\"co\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coloradonewsday.com/news/regional/84008-twin-peaks-sheryl-lee-reveals-blood-disorder-has-left-her-struggling.html|work=Colorado Newsday|title=Twin Peaks' Sheryl Lee reveals blood disorder has left her struggling|date=November 11, 2014|accessdate=March 29, 2015|author=Staff Writer|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402122017/http://www.coloradonewsday.com/news/regional/84008-twin-peaks-sheryl-lee-reveals-blood-disorder-has-left-her-struggling.html|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSheryl Lee is also a [[Teacher]] at [[UCLA School of Theater, Film and Television]].<ref>http://www.tft.ucla.edu/2016/12/sheryl-lee/</ref> Together with her former ''Twin Peaks'' castmate [[Gary Hershberger]] (who played ''Mike Nelson''), Lee teaches actors, directors and writers at their workshop \"The Actor's Director Workshop\".<ref>https://www.theactorsdirectorworkshop.com/who-we-are</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy and activism===\nLee is an avid member of [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] (People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals) and has assertively campaigned against fur and mistreatment of animals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peta.org/features/sheryl-lee.aspx |title=Sheryl Lee Takes a Swipe at Animal Acts |publisher=People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2008, she participated in the 3rd Munchkin's Project Pink annual breast cancer awareness campaign to raise money for breast cancer research.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://members.ebay.com/ws2/eBayISAPI.dll?ViewUserPage&userid=munchkin_inc |title=Munchkin, Inc. \u2013 maker of award-winning infant and toddler products is once again reminding women everywhere \"Don't Duck a Breast Exam\" with the return of its successful Project Pink breast cancer awareness campaign. |date=October 2008 |accessdate= September 10, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.facebook.com/note.php?note_id=35580363389 |title=Sheryl Lee supports breast cancer research |date=October 2008 |accessdate=10 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2008_August_5/ai_n27969442/ |title=Munchkin, Inc. Reminds Women Everywhere \"Don't Duck a Breast Exam\" with Third Annual Project Pink Charity Campaign |publisher=Open Publishing |date=August 5, 2008 |work=FindArticles |accessdate= September 10, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, Lee has also participated in various environmentalist events and charities: In November 2000, she attended the premiere of the public awareness campaign ''Why Are We Here?'', to raise awareness for biodiversity protection,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/November+15+Premiere+of+%27Why+Are+We+Here%3F%27+to+Feature+Bevy+of...-a066873185|title=November 15 Premiere of 'Why Are We Here?' to Feature Bevy of Environmentally-Concerned Celebrities|publisher=TheFreeLibrary.com |date= November 13, 2000|accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref> In 2011, Lee attended the iMatter March in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]] to raise awareness about climate change,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.westword.com/latestword/2011/05/darryl_hannah_sheryl_lee_climate_change_march_photos.php |title=Darryl Hannah, Sheryl \"Laura Palmer\" Lee add star power to climate change march |author=Roberts, Michael |publisher=Village Voice Media |date=May 16, 2011 |work=Westword |accessdate=September 10, 2011 }}</ref> and also supported the  ''Ride for Renewables'' project to promote [[renewable energy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rideforrenewables.com/ride-friends/ |title=Ride Friends |publisher=Ride for Renewables |accessdate= September 29, 2011}}</ref> In December 2011, Lee advocated the protection of wolves and supported the environmental organization [[WildEarth Guardians]]' \"Wolves in the American West\" campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wildearthguardians.org/site/MessageViewer?em_id=6481.0 |title=Actress Sheryl Lee Advocates For Wolves |publisher=WildEarth Guardians |date=December 2011 |accessdate=January 2, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426022301/http://www.wildearthguardians.org/site/MessageViewer?em_id=6481.0 |archive-date=2012-04-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Lee signed environmental activist Tom Weis' open letter calling on President Barack Obama and Governor Mitt Romney to withdraw their support for the construction of the southern leg of [[Keystone XL]], a pipeline that would transport bitumen from Montana to Texas. Other signatories included climate scientist [[James Hansen]] and actors [[Daryl Hannah]], [[Mariel Hemingway]], and [[Ed Begley, Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rideforrenewables.com/2012/09/an-open-letter-to-president-obama-and-governor-romney-on-keystone-xl/ |title= Open Letter to President Obama and Governor Romney: Defend America Against Keystone XL Economic, Public Health & National Security Threat |publisher=Ride for Renewables |date=September 26, 2012 |accessdate=22 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn December 8, 2012, Lee performed poems written by herself as part of a collaborative performance along with artist [[Marina DeBris]], dancer Maya Gabay, and musician Marla Leigh, for the U.S. National Committee for [[UN Women]]'s ''First Annual Special Assembly: Women, Climate Change, and Human Rights''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://generationgreen.tv/women-climate-change-and-human-rights-un-women-usnc-greater-los-angeles-chapter-first-annual-special-assembly/ |title=Women, Climate Change and Human Rights: UN Women-USNC Greater Los Angeles Chapter First Annual Special Assembly |publisher=GenerationGreen.TV |date=17 December 2012 |accessdate=23 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130706141247/http://generationgreen.tv/women-climate-change-and-human-rights-un-women-usnc-greater-los-angeles-chapter-first-annual-special-assembly/ |archivedate=6 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''He's No Hero''\n| Liz \n| Short film\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Wild at Heart (film)|Wild at Heart]]''\n| The Good Witch\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Jersey Girl (1992 film)|Jersey Girl]]''\n| Tara\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Twin Peaks: Fire Walk with Me]]''\n| [[Laura Palmer]]\n| Nominated \u2014 [[Saturn Award for Best Actress]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Female Lead]]\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Mr. Jones (1993 film)|Mr. Jones]]''\n| June\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''The Can''\n| \n| filmed in 1988/89\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Don't Do It (film)|Don't Do It]]''\n| Michelle\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Backbeat (film)|Backbeat]]''\n| [[Astrid Kirchherr]]\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Fall Time (film)|Fall Time]]''\n| Patty / Carol\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Homage''\n| Lucy Samuel\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Notes from Underground#Film|Notes from Underground]]''\n| Liza\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Mother Night (film)|Mother Night]]''\n| Helga Noth / Resi Noth\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Bliss (1997 film)|Bliss]]''\n| Maria\n| \n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[This World, Then the Fireworks (1997 film)|This World, Then the Fireworks]]''\n| Lois Archer\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[The Blood Oranges]]''\n| Fiona\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Vampires (1998 film)|Vampires]]''\n| Katrina\n| [[Fangoria Chainsaw Award]] for Best Supporting Actr