{"title_page": "1973 FA Cup Final", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|                   title = 1973 FA Cup Final\n| image = Old Wembley Stadium (external view).jpg\n| image_size = 200\n|                   event = [[1972\u201373 FA Cup]]\n|                   team1 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n|        team1association =\n|              team1score = 1\n|                   team2 = [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]]\n|        team2association =\n|              team2score = 0\n|                 details =\n|                    date = 5 May 1973\n|                 stadium = [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]]\n|                    city = [[London]]\n|      man_of_the_match1a =\n| man_of_the_match1atitle =\n|      man_of_the_match1b =\n| man_of_the_match1btitle =\n|                 referee = [[Ken Burns (referee)|Ken Burns]]\n|              attendance = 100,000\n|                 weather =\n|                previous = [[1972 FA Cup Final|1972]]\n|                    next = [[1974 FA Cup Final|1974]]\n}}\nThe '''1973 FA Cup Final''' was the 92nd final of the [[FA Cup]]. It took place on 5 May 1973 at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] and was contested between [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], the [[1972 FA Cup Final|previous season]]'s winners and one of the dominant teams in English football at the time, and [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], then playing in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]].\n\nIn one of the biggest shocks in the history of the competition, Sunderland won 1\u20130 to become the first Second Division side to lift the Cup since [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in 1931. It remains Sunderland's only major trophy since [[World War II]]. Sunderland's team were the only FA Cup winners of the 20th century not to field any full internationals, although some of their players were capped later.\n\n==Road to Wembley==\n{|width=100%\n|width=50% valign=top|\n<big>'''Leeds United'''</big><br />\n''Home teams listed first.''\n'''Round 3:''' [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] 1\u20131 Leeds United\n:'''''Replay:''' Leeds United 1\u20131 Norwich City\n:'''''2nd Replay:''' Leeds United 5\u20130 Norwich City (at [[Villa Park]])\n\n'''Round 4:''' Leeds United 2\u20131 [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]\n:&nbsp;\n\n'''Round 5:''' Leeds United 2\u20130 [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|WBA]]\n:&nbsp;\n\n'''Quarter-Final:''' [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] 0\u20131 Leeds United\n\n'''Semi-Final:''' Leeds United 1\u20130 [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n:(at [[Maine Road]], [[Manchester]])\n|width=50% valign=top|\n<big>'''Sunderland'''</big><br />\n''Home teams listed first.''\n'''Round 3:''' [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] 1\u20131 Sunderland\n:'''''Replay:''' Sunderland 2\u20130 Notts County\n:&nbsp;\n\n'''Round 4:''' Sunderland 1\u20131 [[Reading F.C.|Reading]]\n:'''''Replay:''' Reading 1\u20133 Sunderland\n\n'''Round 5:''' [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] 2\u20132 Sunderland\n:'''''Replay:''' Sunderland 3\u20131 Manchester City\n\n'''Quarter-Final:''' Sunderland 2\u20130 [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]]\n\n'''Semi-Final:''' Sunderland 2\u20131 [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n:(at [[Hillsborough Stadium]], [[Sheffield]])\n|}\n\n==Match summary==\n[[File:Ianporterfieldgoal.jpg|thumb|left|The only goal scored]]\n[[File:Bckup260815 011.JPG|thumb|The final match ball with the Golden Boot awarded to [[Ian Porterfield]] of Sunderland]]\nSunderland established their tactics immediately from the kick-off and refused to be intimidated by their more illustrious opponents, tackling fiercely and defiantly with an unremitting determination. Leeds looked anxious, lacking their usual composure. The match itself was decided by two crucial moments that would be talked about for years to come.\n\nAfter 32 minutes Sunderland took the lead when [[Vic Halom]] chested down a corner from [[Billy Hughes (footballer born 1948)|Billy Hughes]]. Assisted by [[David Watson (footballer born 1946)|Dave Watson]] between two defenders, the deflected high ball was controlled by [[Ian Porterfield]] who shot home from 12 yards. Leeds, shocked, battled back with predictable determination. Sunderland\u2019s goalkeeper [[Jimmy Montgomery]] was outstanding, defying Leeds with a string of fine saves and preserving his team\u2019s lead.\n\nThe turning point of the match came midway through the second half. Montgomery dived to palm away a close range header from Trevor Cherry. It fell into the path of Lorimer who blasted goalward from 10 yards but Montgomery managed to divert the ball on to the underside of the bar and Malone scrambled the ball clear. The save has been compared with that made by [[England national football team|England\u2019s]] [[Gordon Banks]] in the [[1970 FIFA World Cup]] match against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=GGgVawPscysC&dat=19730507&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|title= Dream comes true for Sunderland|date=7 May 1973|work=Glasgow Herald (page 4)|accessdate=23 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe North East team survived more pressure from Leeds to secure a notable upset.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://roker-roar.com/pauldays/navbar/1973.html|title= 1973 FA Cup Rune|date=|work=Roker Roar.com|accessdate=23 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe 1973 showpiece is the only FA Cup final to be played with an orange ball.\n\nSunderland's FA Cup record, \"Sunderland All the Way\", was recorded by comedian [[Bobby Knoxall]].<ref name=\"echo\">{{cite news |author=Tim Booler and Jessica Forster |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Comic-legend-Bobby-Knoxall-dies.5477981.jp |title=Comic legend Bobby Knoxall dies |work=Sunderland Echo |date=2009-07-21 |access-date=22 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090727161637/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Comic-legend-Bobby-Knoxall-dies.5477981.jp |archive-date=27 July 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Match details==\n{{football box\n|date=5 May 1973<br />15:00 [[Western European Summer Time|BST]]\n|team1=[[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]]\n|score=0\u20131\n|team2=[[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n|report=[https://web.archive.org/web/20071028062322/http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1973.htm (Report)]\n|goals1=\n|goals2=[[Ian Porterfield|Porterfield]] {{goal|32}}\n|stadium=[[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]], [[London]]\n|attendance=100,000\n|referee=[[Ken Burns (referee)|Ken Burns]], [[Stourbridge]] }}\n\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la =\n | pattern_b  =\n | pattern_ra =\n | leftarm    = FFFFFF\n | body       = FFFFFF\n | rightarm   = FFFFFF\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = FFFFFF\n | title      = Leeds United\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _red_stripes\n | pattern_b  = _whitestripes\n | pattern_ra = _red_stripes\n | pattern_sh =\n | pattern_so = _whitetop\n | leftarm    = FFFFFF\n | body       = FF0000\n | rightarm   = FFFFFF\n | shorts     = 000000\n | socks      = FF0000\n | title      = Sunderland\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|colspan=\"4\"|\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[David Harvey (footballer)|David Harvey]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Paul Reaney]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Trevor Cherry]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''4''' ||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Billy Bremner]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Paul Madeley]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Norman Hunter (footballer)|Norman Hunter]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''7''' ||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Peter Lorimer]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''8''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Allan Clarke (footballer)|Allan Clarke]]\n|-\n|FW||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Mick Jones (footballer, born 1945)|Mick Jones]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|IRL}} [[Johnny Giles]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Eddie Gray (footballer, born 1948)|Eddie Gray]] {{suboff|75}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Substitute:'''\n|-\n|MF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|WAL}} [[Terry Yorath]] {{subon|75}}\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Don Revie]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|colspan=\"4\"|\n|-\n!width=\"30\"| !!width=\"30\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Jimmy Montgomery]]\n|-\n|RB ||'''2''' ||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Dick Malone]]\n|-\n|LB ||'''3''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Ron Guthrie]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''4''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Micky Horswill]]\n|-\n|CB ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[David Watson (footballer born 1946)|David Watson]]\n|-\n|CB ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Richie Pitt]]\n|-\n|RCM ||'''7''' ||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Bobby Kerr (footballer, born 1947)|Bobby Kerr]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|RW ||'''8''' ||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Billy Hughes (footballer, born 1948)|Billy Hughes]]\n|-\n|ST ||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Vic Halom]]\n|-\n|LCM ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Ian Porterfield]]\n|-\n|LW ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Dennis Tueart]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Substitute:'''\n|-\n|CB ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[David Young (footballer, born 1945)|David Young]]\n|-\n|colspan=4|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Bob Stokoe]]\n|}\n|}\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n| width=50% valign=top|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes.\n*30 minutes of extra-time if necessary.\n*Replay if scores still level.\n*One named substitute.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[[File:1973facuphomecoming.jpg|thumb|left|Fans line the streets as the Sunderland team return home after winning the FA Cup]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090228215214/http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=258940 Game facts] at soccerbase.com\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/1973/05/06/sfglee06.xml Match report in \"Daily Telegraph\"]\n\n{{FA Cup Finals}}\n{{1972\u201373 in English football}}\n{{Leeds United A.F.C. matches}}\n{{Sunderland A.F.C. matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1973 Fa Cup Final}}\n[[Category:1972\u201373 FA Cup|Final]]\n[[Category:FA Cup Finals]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. matches|FA Cup Final 1973]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. matches|FA Cup Final 1973]]\n[[Category:Events at Wembley Stadium]]\n[[Category:1973 sports events in London|FA Cup Final]]\n[[Category:May 1973 sports events in the United Kingdom|FA Cup Final]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|                   title = 1973 FA Cup Final\n| image = Old Wembley Stadium (external view).jpg\n| image_size = 200\n|                   event = [[1972\u201373 FA Cup]]\n|                   team1 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n|        team1association =\n|              team1score = 1\n|                   team2 = [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]]\n|        team2association =\n|              team2score = 0\n|                 details =\n|                    date = 5 May 1973\n|                 stadium = [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]]\n|                    city = [[London]]\n|      man_of_the_match1a =\n| man_of_the_match1atitle =\n|      man_of_the_match1b =\n| man_of_the_match1btitle =\n|                 referee = [[Ken Burns (referee)|Ken Burns]]\n|              attendance = 100,000\n|                 weather =\n|                previous = [[1972 FA Cup Final|1972]]\n|                    next = [[1974 FA Cup Final|1974]]\n}}\nThe '''1973 FA Cup Final''' was the 92nd final of the [[FA Cup]]. It took place on 5 May 1973 at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] and was contested between [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], the [[1972 FA Cup Final|previous season]]'s winners and one of the dominant teams in English football at the time, and [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], then playing in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]].\n\nIn one of the biggest shocks in the history of the competition, Sunderland won 1\u20130 to become the first Second Division side to lift the Cup since [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in 1931. It remains Sunderland's only major trophy since [[World War II]]. Sunderland's team were the only FA Cup winners of the 20th century not to field any full internationals, although some of their players were capped later.\n\n==Road to Wembley==\n{|width=100%\n|width=50% valign=top|\n<big>'''Leeds United'''</big><br />\n''Home teams listed first.''\n'''Round 3:''' [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] 1\u20131 Leeds United\n:'''''Replay:''' Leeds United 1\u20131 Norwich City\n:'''''2nd Replay:''' Leeds United 5\u20130 Norwich City (at [[Villa Park]])\n\n'''Round 4:''' Leeds United 2\u20131 [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]]\n:&nbsp;\n\n'''Round 5:''' Leeds United 2\u20130 [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|WBA]]\n:&nbsp;\n\n'''Quarter-Final:''' [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] 0\u20131 Leeds United\n\n'''Semi-Final:''' Leeds United 1\u20130 [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n:(at [[Maine Road]], [[Manchester]])\n|width=50% valign=top|\n<big>'''Sunderland'''</big><br />\n''Home teams listed first.''\n'''Round 3:''' [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] 1\u20131 Sunderland\n:'''''Replay:''' Sunderland 2\u20130 Notts County\n:&nbsp;\n\n'''Round 4:''' Sunderland 1\u20131 [[Reading F.C.|Reading]]\n:'''''Replay:''' Reading 1\u20133 Sunderland\n\n'''Round 5:''' [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] 2\u20132 Sunderland\n:'''''Replay:''' Sunderland 3\u20131 Manchester City\n\n'''Quarter-Final:''' Sunderland 2\u20130 [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]]\n\n'''Semi-Final:''' Sunderland 2\u20131 [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n:(at [[Hillsborough Stadium]], [[Sheffield]])\n|}\n\n==Match summary==\n[[File:Ianporterfieldgoal.jpg|thumb|left|The only goal scored]]\n[[File:Bckup260815 011.JPG|thumb|The final match ball with the Golden Boot awarded to [[Ian Porterfield]] of Sunderland]]\nSunderland established their tactics immediately from the kick-off and refused to be intimidated by their more illustrious opponents, tackling fiercely and defiantly with an unremitting determination. Leeds looked anxious, lacking their usual composure. The match itself was decided by two crucial moments that would be talked about for years to come.\n\nAfter 32 minutes Sunderland took the lead when [[Vic Halom]] chested down a corner from [[Billy Hughes (footballer born 1948)|Billy Hughes]]. Assisted by [[David Watson (footballer born 1946)|Dave Watson]] between two defenders, the deflected high ball was controlled by [[Ian Porterfield]] who shot home from 12 yards. Leeds, shocked, battled back with predictable determination. Sunderland\u2019s goalkeeper [[Jimmy Montgomery]] was outstanding, defying Leeds with a string of fine saves and preserving his team\u2019s lead.\n\nThe turning point of the match came midway through the second half. Montgomery dived to palm away a close range header from Trevor Cherry. It fell into the path of Lorimer who blasted goalward from 10 yards but Montgomery managed to divert the ball on to the underside of the bar and Malone scrambled the ball clear. The save has been compared with that made by [[England national football team|England\u2019s]] [[Gordon Banks]] in the [[1970 FIFA World Cup]] match against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=GGgVawPscysC&dat=19730507&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|title= Dream comes true for Sunderland|date=7 May 1973|work=Glasgow Herald (page 4)|accessdate=23 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe North East team survived more pressure from Leeds to secure a notable upset.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://roker-roar.com/pauldays/navbar/1973.html|title= 1973 FA Cup Rune|date=|work=Roker Roar.com|accessdate=23 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe 1973 showpiece is the only FA Cup final ever to be played with an orange ball.\n\nSunderland's FA Cup record, \"Sunderland All the Way\", was recorded by comedian [[Bobby Knoxall]].<ref name=\"echo\">{{cite news |author=Tim Booler and Jessica Forster |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Comic-legend-Bobby-Knoxall-dies.5477981.jp |title=Comic legend Bobby Knoxall dies |work=Sunderland Echo |date=2009-07-21 |access-date=22 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090727161637/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Comic-legend-Bobby-Knoxall-dies.5477981.jp |archive-date=27 July 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Match details==\n{{football box\n|date=5 May 1973<br />15:00 [[Western European Summer Time|BST]]\n|team1=[[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]]\n|score=0\u20131\n|team2=[[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n|report=[https://web.archive.org/web/20071028062322/http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1973.htm (Report)]\n|goals1=\n|goals2=[[Ian Porterfield|Porterfield]] {{goal|32}}\n|stadium=[[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]], [[London]]\n|attendance=100,000\n|referee=[[Ken Burns (referee)|Ken Burns]], [[Stourbridge]] }}\n\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la =\n | pattern_b  =\n | pattern_ra =\n | leftarm    = FFFFFF\n | body       = FFFFFF\n | rightarm   = FFFFFF\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = FFFFFF\n | title      = Leeds United\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _red_stripes\n | pattern_b  = _whitestripes\n | pattern_ra = _red_stripes\n | pattern_sh =\n | pattern_so = _whitetop\n | leftarm    = FFFFFF\n | body       = FF0000\n | rightarm   = FFFFFF\n | shorts     = 000000\n | socks      = FF0000\n | title      = Sunderland\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|colspan=\"4\"|\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[David Harvey (footballer)|David Harvey]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Paul Reaney]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Trevor C